so this will handle the config files that, in 'normal' setups, would belong in ~/.config/.. What about ones that normally live elsewhere?

Do not worry about having more questions; this is exactly how you master NixOS!Your symlink mapping loop handles everything inside ~/.config/, but for files that live outside that directory, Home Manager provides specialized, 
built-in options to place them exactly where they need to go.
Here is how you handle files that live in your home root directory, the /etc/ directory, or standalone files

.1. Files in the Home Root (e.g., ~/.zshenv, ~/.bashrc)If a file needs to live directly in /home/yourusername/, you use home.file instead of xdg.configFile. 

You can use the exact same mkOutOfStoreSymlink trick:

nixhome.file.".zshenv" = {
  source = config.lib.file.mkOutOfStoreSymlink "${dotfiles}/zshenv";
};

Use code with caution.

2. Global System Files (e.g., /etc/vconsole.conf, /etc/hosts)If a configuration belongs to the entire machine (not just your user), 
Home Manager cannot touch it. Instead, you configure it globally inside configuration.nix.NixOS has native options for almost every global file:

Instead of editing /etc/hosts, 
you add: networking.extraHosts = "127.0.0.1 custom.local";

Instead of editing /etc/environment, you add: environment.variables = { EDITOR = "nvim"; };

If you ever need to force a raw, custom text file directly into /etc/ without using a built-in helper, 
NixOS gives you the environment.etc 

attribute:nixenvironment.etc."custom-system-config.conf".text = ''
  setting = true
  another_setting = false
'';


Use code with caution.

3. SSH Configurations (~/.ssh/config)SSH is highly sensitive about file permissions and will completely reject symlinks that are too open. 
Because of this, using raw symlinks for SSH can cause connection errors.
The proper "Nix way" is to let Home Manager generate the file securely for you inside 

home.nix:nixprograms.ssh = {
  enable = true;
  matchBlocks = {
    "github.com" = {
      hostname = "github.com";
      user = "git";
      identityFile = "~/.ssh/id_ed25519";
    };
  };
};

Use code with caution.

How to choose which tool to use:

~/.config/: Stick to your automated xdg.configFile mapping loop.
Elsewhere in /home/: Use home.file with a manual mkOutOfStoreSymlink target.
System-wide /etc/: Use native NixOS configuration options inside configuration.nix.


